🚀 1. What is a Condition Variable?

In Java, a condition variable is represented by:

👉 Condition

It is used with:

👉 ReentrantLock

🧠 Core Idea
Lock → Condition → Wait / Signal

👉 Threads can:

Wait for a condition
Be notified when condition is met
🔥 2. Why not wait() / notify()?

Old way (synchronized):

wait();
notify();

Problems:

❌ Only one wait-set per object
❌ Hard to manage multiple conditions
❌ Less control

✅ Condition solves this

👉 Multiple condition queues per lock

⚙️ 3. Basic Working Example
🎯 Problem: Producer–Consumer
💻 Code
import java.util.concurrent.locks.*;

public class ConditionExample {

    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    private final Condition notEmpty = lock.newCondition();

    private int data = 0;
    private boolean available = false;

    public void produce(int value) throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            while (available) {
                notEmpty.await();
            }

            data = value;
            available = true;

            System.out.println("Produced: " + value);

            notEmpty.signal();

        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public void consume() throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            while (!available) {
                notEmpty.await();
            }

            System.out.println("Consumed: " + data);
            available = false;

            notEmpty.signal();

        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ConditionExample obj = new ConditionExample();

        new Thread(() -> {
            try {
                for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
                    obj.produce(i);
                }
            } catch (Exception e) {}
        }).start();

        new Thread(() -> {
            try {
                for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
                    obj.consume();
                }
            } catch (Exception e) {}
        }).start();
    }
}
🧠 4. How it Works Internally

When you call:

condition.await();

👉 Steps:

Release lock 🔓
Add thread to condition queue
Block (park thread)

When:

condition.signal();

👉 Steps:

Move thread from condition queue → lock queue
Thread competes to acquire lock again
🔥 5. Two Queues (VERY IMPORTANT)
Condition Queue → waiting threads
AQS Queue → lock acquisition queue
🧠 Flow
await() → move to condition queue
signal() → move to AQS queue
⚠️ 6. CRITICAL RULES (MUST KNOW)
❗ 1. Always use while, NOT if
while (!condition) {
    await();
}

👉 Because of spurious wakeups

❗ 2. Must hold lock before await/signal
lock.lock();
condition.await(); // OK
condition.await(); // ❌ IllegalMonitorStateException
❗ 3. Signal does NOT release lock
condition.signal();

👉 Thread wakes but waits for lock

❗ 4. Missed signal problem

If signal happens before await → thread may wait forever

🔥 7. Multiple Conditions (BIG ADVANTAGE)
Condition notFull = lock.newCondition();
Condition notEmpty = lock.newCondition();
💻 Example (Bounded Buffer)
import java.util.concurrent.locks.*;

public class BoundedBuffer {

    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    private final Condition notFull = lock.newCondition();
    private final Condition notEmpty = lock.newCondition();

    private int count = 0;
    private final int capacity = 5;

    public void produce() throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            while (count == capacity) {
                notFull.await();
            }

            count++;
            System.out.println("Produced → " + count);

            notEmpty.signal();

        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public void consume() throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            while (count == 0) {
                notEmpty.await();
            }

            System.out.println("Consumed → " + count);
            count--;

            notFull.signal();

        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}
⚔️ 8. Condition vs wait/notify
Feature	Condition	wait/notify
Multiple queues	✅	❌
Explicit lock	✅	❌
Flexibility	High	Low
⚠️ 9. Real Production Bugs
❌ Lost signal
signal() happens before await()

👉 Thread stuck forever

❌ Deadlock

Wrong condition usage

❌ Starvation

Threads not getting signal

🔥 10. Advanced Methods
await()
awaitUninterruptibly()
awaitNanos()
await(long time, TimeUnit unit)

signal()
signalAll()
⚠️ signal vs signalAll
Method	Behavior
signal()	wakes 1 thread
signalAll()	wakes all threads

👉 Use signalAll() when:

multiple conditions
risk of missed signal
🧠 11. Mental Model
Lock → Condition → Wait → Signal → Re-acquire lock
🚀 12. Interview Killer Answer

Condition variables allow threads to wait and be notified under a lock.
They provide multiple wait queues and finer control compared to wait/notify.